  "game_explanation": "This three-player game features two chip types with very different strategic roles. Green chips are common-value: everyone knows they are worth $0.50 to each player. Red chips are private-value: each player only knows their own red value, but we as analysts know dog= $0.30, buffalo= $0.10, cat= $0.40. Publicly, players only know that red chips lie somewhere in a broad range ($0.10–$1.00), so they are uncertain about how much others value red relative to green.\n\nBecause green is strictly more valuable than red for every player given the true values, pure efficiency and pure self-interest would both suggest that everyone should try to trade away red for green whenever they can. However, each player only sees their own value, so they must infer others' values from proposals. Slightly subtle incentives emerge:\n- cat privately has the highest red value ($0.40), but red is still worse than green. Cat has the strongest reason to acquire red if the ratio is favorable, yet will still be cautious about giving up too many greens.\n- dog has intermediate red value ($0.30). Dog would like to acquire red if it is cheap in greens, and will especially welcome deals that turn greens into more total value via red, but will not pay a 1:1 green-for-red price.\n- buffalo has the lowest red value ($0.10). Red is nearly junk relative to green. Buffalo has by far the strongest incentive to unload red in exchange for green, even at aggressive rates (e.g., several red for a single green), but must make offers attractive enough that others think they are gaining.\n\nUncertainty is asymmetric: each player knows green is $0.50 but only knows their own red value. They can safely assume that nobody will trade green for red at a rate that obviously loses value under any plausible red value (e.g., 1 green for 1 red). So compelling trades are likely to be multi-for-one or 1-for-2 type ratios, signaling that the proposer is willing to give substantial red to get green or vice versa.\n\nPersonas add texture to how aggressively they bargain:\n- dog appears cooperative, tolerant of inequality, and not strongly punitive. She will likely make fair, moderate trades that share surplus and may accept slightly unbalanced offers if they still leave her better off, especially early while exploration is valuable.\n- buffalo is more cautious and structured, with low initial trust. He is unlikely to send a very generous deal unless it is clearly in his self-interest (e.g., shedding his low-value red for green), and will reject speculative or unclear offers. He is also analytically strong and probably calculates implicit per-chip value more than others.\n- cat is somewhat self-interested and shorter-term, but tolerant of unequal outcomes. He is willing to grab a good deal even if it looks somewhat unfair to the other party, but will not overthink fine-grained expected values. He may accept offers that are clearly positive for him without worrying too hard about what they reveal about others' values.\n\nThe three-round structure with fixed proposer order (dog, then buffalo, then cat each round) means each player gets three chances to propose but no formal opportunity for counteroffers within a turn. Learning is incremental and based on observing who accepts what. Early in the game, trades will likely be more conservative and symmetric, with players probing others' willingness to swap red and green. As the game approaches the final round, proposers may push more aggressively to realize any remaining gains: buffalo trying to dump red for green, dog and cat trying to accumulate modestly profitable packages, while still avoiding obvious value-destroying deals.\n\nA key strategic tension is between risk and partner selection. If two non-senders both accept, the recipient is random, creating lottery-like risk for the proposer. Proposers must choose deal structures that are attractive enough that at least one player will accept but not so attractive that multiple will compete, unless the proposer is indifferent about which partner they get. Given the small number of rounds and the absence of future retaliation, we expect mostly simple, small-bundle trades (e.g., 1–3 chips) designed to create clear margins for both sides and to reduce uncertainty over others' valuations.",
