      "round_explanation": "By the final round, a clear pattern has emerged: buffalo is willing to offer many red for a single green, revealing that his red value is quite low. Dog has repeatedly accepted such deals, accumulating green while giving up red at favorable terms. Cat has also accepted red-heavy deals for green but is now green-poor and red-rich after earlier trades.\n\nStrategically, round 2 is the last chance to adjust portfolios. Dog, with relatively high green holdings and moderate red, might either try to squeeze a final small gain or simply avoid risky trades that could reduce her advantage. Buffalo, nearing the end, may attempt one more aggressive red-for-green offer if he still holds red, but also might stop if marginal gains are small or if others seem saturated and unwilling to give up any more green. Cat, seeing his shortage of green and higher red valuation, may look for a slightly better price than earlier if he can get it, but with only one turn left and cautious partners, he may be forced to pass on marginal or negative-value deals. Rejection becomes more common as the opportunity for future compensation disappears.",
