  "game_explanation": "This is a three-player, three-round bargaining game over two chip types, RED and GREEN. GREEN is common-value at $0.50 for everyone. RED has divergent private values: otter values RED and GREEN equally at $0.50; peacock highly values RED at $0.80; badger values RED weakly at $0.20. All start with 10 RED and 10 GREEN. Because players only know their own values, they must infer others’ valuations from observed proposals and accept/reject behavior.\n\nIncentives: Peacock is naturally a strong net buyer of RED and net seller of GREEN (since GREEN=$0.50 to her and RED=$0.80). Badger is a natural net seller of RED (worth $0.20) in exchange for GREEN ($0.50). Otter is approximately indifferent between colors but somewhat conservative and self-protective, and will not want to make obviously dominated trades. Efficient gains come mainly from moving RED from badger to peacock, possibly via direct trades like GREEN-for-RED at favorable terms to both. Otter can potentially act as an intermediary but has weak private incentive to engage in complex arbitrage.\n\nPersonas shape how hard they press these incentives. Peacock is strongly prosocial and generous in other tasks, so she is likely to propose relatively generous RED-buy offers and accept trades that also leave counterparties clearly better off. Badger is moderately prosocial and tolerant of inequality; he will accept small gains easily and rarely reject. Otter is cooperative in principle but made very low offers in simple allocation tasks; combined with uncertainty aversion, she is likely to be cautious, avoid extreme or complicated offers, and shy away from trades that might look one-sided or might be rejected.\n\nDynamics and uncertainty: In early rounds players know only that RED’s public range is $0.10–$1.00. They must guess whether others are high-RED or low-RED types. When a player offers to buy RED at a premium relative to GREEN, that reveals they probably value RED highly. When someone sells RED cheaply, that reveals low RED valuation. Rejections of highly favorable offers can signal that a player also values the chip being sold. Because accept decisions are simultaneous and proposers cannot choose among multiple acceptors, there is also strategic uncertainty: if both potential recipients like the deal, the realized partner is random.\n\nGiven only three rounds and one proposal per player per round, each player will usually try to make reasonably straightforward, interpretable offers that exploit their likely comparative advantage without needing long-term reputation building. We should expect: (1) peacock to drive most value creation through RED-buy offers, particularly targeting badger once it becomes clear he accepts modest improvements; (2) badger to accept RED-sell offers that give him even a small Green gain; and (3) otter to make at most mildly speculative or information-seeking trades, and to sometimes decline trades that appear to risk leaving her worse off or that look too lopsided against her own valuation priors.",
