alanced or slightly favorable GREEN-for-RED trades, probing whether anyone will take them. Buffalo, more analytical and with higher logical reasoning, will quickly recognize that acquiring RED cheaply is good, but will not want to reveal her strong preference too clearly in the first move. As proposals and acceptances occur, players can update beliefs: if someone eagerly takes RED or insists on selling RED only at a premium, others infer higher RED valuation for that player. By round 1, there is more information about who seems interested in RED, and by round 2 they will likely attempt to fine-tune trades to capture remaining surplus, though the limited number of turns caps complexity.\n\nRandomization of recipient when multiple players accept adds a subtle externality: a proposer wanting a specific partner cannot ensure it. This discourages offering extremely generous deals that both other players would like, and encourages designing proposals that mainly attract the single, intended responder (for example, buffalo designing a deal that is especially good for low-RED-value types, or cat/camel structuring offers that mainly buffalo wants). Given the personas, none of the players are strongly altruistic; they aim to increase their own payoff and will decline trades that clearly reduce it. Overall, we expect: (i) multiple GREEN-for-RED trade offers, (ii) buffalo more often on the accepting side of RED purchases, (iii) cat and camel experimenting with selling RED and, after seeing responses, possibly softening their terms to close at least one deal before the game ends.",
