 seek clear gains in value and avoid complicated or riskier offers, especially ones that feel too generous to others. Whale is also prosocial and strategic, willing to accept small but positive expected gains, and may be more active in exploiting arbitrage between their high red value and others’ likely lower red valuations. Over three rounds, players will update their beliefs from observed pricing patterns (e.g., who seems eager to give up reds) and may adjust their offers accordingly. Because each round has only one proposal per player and there is no carryover beyond this game, they face a finite horizon: it is sensible to accept any clearly positive trade rather than wait for a perfect one. We forecast moderately active trading, especially between whale and iguana, gradually shifting red chips to whale and greens to iguana, with owl engaging opportunistically but not aggressively.\n\nThe reconstructed game below is one plausible full-path forecast: every turn involves a feasible, strategically reasonable proposal given each player’s private valuation, the public history, and their prosocial but payoff-oriented tendencies. Trades that yield obvious value gains are often accepted; ambiguous or thin-margin trades are declined.",
