ders move simultaneously, a proposer cannot target a specific partner; if both accept, the realized partner is chosen at random. This uncertainty makes highly generous, multi-acceptance-attractive proposals riskier for the proposer if she has a clear preferred partner.\n\nGiven only three rounds and one proposal per player per round, there is limited time for complex signaling or reputation-building. Most proposals will plausibly be simple one-step chip trades (\"I give you some of X, you give me some of Y\") that are locally value-improving for the proposer and at least mildly attractive for at least one responder. Early in the game, players may test conservative trades that are roughly value-neutral under symmetric valuations. Over time, camel is likely to shade more toward trades that increase her RED holdings at the cost of GREEN, while butterfly and especially alligator will respond selectively, accepting only where the improvement in their own subjective chip value is clear. Because RED is actually more valuable to camel than to the others, mutually beneficial trades should exist, but incomplete information and risk preferences can easily lead to declined offers, especially from the more self-protective alligator.\n\nThe following forecast reconstructs one plausible complete game path under these incentives and personas, assuming moderately cautious but value-seeking behavior, with camel trying somewhat prosocial but advantageous RED-for-GREEN trades, butterfly exploring small-bet, seemingly fair swaps, and alligator remaining very conservative and opportunistic in what she accepts.",
