proposal per player and there are just three rounds, there is limited time to discover others’ values. Early moves typically explore the market: Duck will test dumping BLUE for GREEN/RED at modest prices; Lion will feel out how much GREEN they can obtain for their somewhat disfavored RED/BLUE; Tiger will try to accumulate RED/BLUE using GREEN as payment, being careful not to overpay in ways that might reveal desperate demand.\n\nA key uncertainty is how much the others value BLUE. Tiger sees BLUE as extremely valuable and is willing to give substantial GREEN or even RED for it, but since Duck and Lion each only know their own values, they do not know whether they are facing a high- or low-BLUE opponent. Similarly, others do not know Tiger’s strong preference for RED/BLUE over GREEN. Over the course of the three rounds, accepted trades gradually reveal that Tiger is willing to give up GREEN for colored chips, Lion prefers GREEN to colored chips, and Duck wants to offload BLUE. This drives a rough pattern: trades that move BLUE and some RED toward Tiger and GREEN toward Duck/Lion, but with frictions from incomplete information and somewhat demanding acceptance thresholds, especially for Lion and Tiger.\n\nThe forecast below follows this logic: early exploratory offers that are somewhat self-serving and often declined, followed by gradually more generous but still individually profitable trades as players react to revealed willingness to trade. The game ends with a modest but non-maximal reallocation of chips, reflecting limited time and information.",
