 with medium thresholds for fairness and self-gain. Camel is very tolerant of low personal payoffs, highly trusting, and strategically flexible, so he is willing to accept many trades that yield even small improvements.\n\nOver the game, we expect: (1) squid tries to move out of red into blue or green, often offering generous terms to ensure acceptance; (2) badger uses green and perhaps blue to accumulate red, yet will avoid overpaying if a trade sacrifices too much value; (3) camel is relatively accommodating, frequently accepting offers that are even slightly positive and occasionally proposing trades to convert low-value reds into higher-value blues or at least stable-value greens. Because all players value green equally, many trades use green as the payment chip to manage risk under incomplete information. The final distribution is likely to show squid holding more blue, badger with extra red (and possibly blue), and camel ending with a mix that reflects opportunistic acceptance rather than aggressive optimization.\n\nThe forecasted game below assumes moderately rational behavior constrained by incomplete information and these social/value profiles: no one takes dominated trades; near-fair, slightly positive deals for the responder are usually accepted; and as rounds progress, players react to the pattern of which offers others have accepted so far.",
