 tendencies. They may propose hard-nosed deals (especially when they see an edge) but are also willing to accept low but positive-gain offers. They may be opportunistic in snapping up clear improvements.\n\nBargaining dynamics and uncertainty:\n- Everyone sees chip counts and trade history but not values. So early trades double as signals: if someone actively buys a color, others can infer that color might be relatively valuable to them. This feedback can shape later proposals.\n- Because responders decide simultaneously and the partner is randomly chosen if multiple accept, senders must craft offers acceptable to at least one counterpart but robust to the risk that the more/less preferred partner might be selected. They cannot safely target a specific partner.\n- With only three rounds (nine total turns), there is limited time to refine beliefs. The likely pattern is that early proposals are somewhat conservative and use green as the payment currency, while later ones may pivot into more tailored, higher-margin swaps once some information is inferred from prior trades.\n\nIn the forecast below, trades are chosen to (a) be individually rational in terms of each player’s own unknown valuations, (b) align with the personas’ risk and social tendencies, and (c) allow modest belief-updating via observed actions. We track a single coherent path of play: exactly which offers are made, who accepts, and how holdings and incentives evolve over the three rounds.",
