  "game_explanation": "This three-player bargaining game features privately valued red, blue, and purple chips plus a common-value green chip. All players start with 10 of each chip type. Each player knows only their own values and must infer others’ preferences from observed trades. The key private-value pattern is that squid highly values red ($1.00) and moderately values purple ($0.50) but has low value for blue ($0.30); otter highly values red ($0.90) and blue ($0.80) but dislikes purple ($0.20); peacock is relatively balanced and especially likes purple ($0.90) and blue ($0.80) with moderate red ($0.60). Greens are always worth $0.50 to everyone. Efficient reallocation would concentrate red with squid and otter, purple with peacock and squid, and blue with peacock and otter, using green as a neutral medium when needed. However, no player sees the full structure, and all are risk-averse enough to avoid trades that might give away something they later realize was underpriced.\n\nPersona-wise, otter is the most self-protective, sends least in trust tasks, and is comfortable offering very little to others; in this game, otter is unlikely to make generous trades and will try to cheaply accumulate high-value reds and blues. Squid is cautious and somewhat cooperative but with low trust-game giving; squid will accept clearly profitable trades but is unlikely to sacrifice value to help others. Peacock is more tolerant of unequal outcomes and somewhat more trusting, with higher cognitive structure and preference for predictable, low-risk gains; peacock is most likely to initiate balanced-seeming trades that offer the other side a visible gain, even if slightly favorable to peacock. Across three short rounds, no binding agreements or side payments exist, and there is a further layer of uncertainty: when both non-senders accept, the final partner is chosen randomly. That randomization discourages highly targeted “favoring” of one specific partner and encourages offers that are at least modestly profitable for both potential responders.\n\nStrategically, early in the game we expect small, relatively symmetric trades that look safe under many possible valuations (e.g., swapping one chip for one or two greens, or exchanging obviously disliked colors like purple for more attractive colors like red). As the game progresses and everyone has seen at least one or two proposals, they gain partial information: for example, a player who sees someone repeatedly trying to buy red with green at a premium might infer high red value for that player. Still, with only three rounds, learning is limited and most choices will reflect coarse heuristics (e.g., treat green as a safe baseline, avoid trading away chips that you suspect might be important, and only accept trades that improve current portfolio value by a clear margin). Because greens are common-value and moderately priced, they naturally play the role of a low-friction medium of exchange; but players with stronger preferences (like squid for red or otter’s dislike of purple) will also try direct color-for-color deals that reallocate across mismatched tastes. Overall, we forecast modest reallocation of red and purple in ways that benefit squid and peacock, with otter attempting to squeeze surplus from trades and often declining unless the immediate value gain is clear.\n\nBelow is one plausible complete playthrough, consistent with the rules, private values, personas, and the exogenous proposer order.",
