der will react or whether they will ultimately be selected.\n\nPersonality-wise, all three profiles look relatively cooperative and tolerant of unequal outcomes, with low ultimatum rejection rates and reasonable offers in prior allocation tasks. That suggests that in this bargaining context they are willing to accept small individual gains rather than hold out for perfect trades, and they may occasionally make somewhat generous proposals that leave noticeable surplus for the trading partner. Whale and iguana both show very high trust-game send amounts and appear comfortable initiating exchanges, which makes it plausible that they will make active, non-exploitative offers rather than purely extreme, one-sided trades. Duck has slightly more mixed trust behavior but high logical reasoning and patience, so she is likely to accept solid but not spectacular gains and to propose trades that are individually profitable while modestly beneficial to others. Overall, the likely play is a sequence of small, incremental trades that gradually reveal preferences: early offers feel somewhat conservative and exploratory, while later ones become more tailored as participants infer that whale and duck really want purple and blue more than iguana does, and iguana is relatively indifferent and happy to gain modest value from colors she doesn't prioritize.\n\nIn this forecast, we assume players do some intuitive reasoning: (a) a color someone is willing to offer may be one they value less; (b) a color someone repeatedly tries to acquire is likely one they value more; (c) offers that are too lopsided in value space will be rejected. Given shared prosocial tendencies, we bias toward trades that are roughly balanced or slightly favor the responder in subjective value, especially early in the game when proposers may overpay to ensure acceptance rather than risk repeated declines. As the game progresses, some of that excess generosity is trimmed as players learn and realize there is limited time (three rounds) to adjust their inventories.",
