ncentives:\n- Alligator has strong demand for blue and good demand for red; she is relatively indifferent between purple and green but slightly prefers purple. She will try to acquire blue and red while using green or some purple as payment, but she must be cautious: others may also value blue and red highly.\n- Dolphin wants red most and dislikes purple, but blue is still good. She is more willing to give up green and purple. Social preferences suggest she may propose relatively generous, safe trades that are clearly positive for at least one other player and not obviously exploitative.\n- Duck wants red and blue and dislikes purple. Green is modest but safe. She is less inclined to initiate trusting trades but is willing to accept clearly advantageous offers. She is unlikely to pay much for purple unless the trade is clearly favorable in value terms.\n\nStrategically, the main difficulty is coordination under uncertainty: any request/offer pattern such as \"I buy red with purple\" reveals hints about valuations and beliefs. Proposers must ensure that at least one opponent perceives a gain, knowing that if both accept, the partner is chosen randomly. This random tie-breaking discourages offers that are only attractive to one very specific counterpart unless the other would obviously reject.\n\nAcross three rounds, each player proposes once per round in fixed order (Alligator, then Dolphin, then Duck). As the game proceeds, they observe who accepts what, updating beliefs about which colors others like or dislike. Participants’ task histories suggest they tolerate some inequality and are not strongly punitive, so they are more likely to accept modest but clear gains even if the proposer benefits more. Given the short horizon (three rounds, nine proposals), they will focus on straightforward, locally beneficial trades rather than elaborate signaling strategies.\n\nThe forecast below reconstructs one plausible path for the full game: each turn specifies a concrete trade, predicted accept/decline responses, and whether the trade executes, using the actual private valuations as an analyst-side guide while respecting that the players themselves only know their own values during play.",
