 the proposer and potentially high-value to themselves, and they may try to arbitrage that. Random resolution when multiple players accept introduces strategic risk: when a sender makes an attractive offer to the whole table, they cannot control who accepts, so they may shade terms to avoid unintentionally subsidizing the wrong counterpart. Over three short rounds (nine total proposals), there is limited time for learning, so players will tend to stick to simple, obviously improving trades from their own perspective: trading away their lowest-value color (for zebra, blue; for pig, purple; for swan, red) in exchange for higher-value colors or green. By the end of the game, we expect zebra to be heavier in red and purple, swan heavier in blue and purple, and pig to accumulate extra green or trade toward either red or blue if favorable terms appear. Some value will remain unrealized due to private information and the coarse, one-color-per-side trade restriction.",
