voiding offers so generous that both respond yes and the proposer ends up partnering with whichever counterparty is randomly chosen, potentially one who is less beneficial in future rounds. Given the repeated-round structure and public history, players can adapt their priors about others' values as they see patterns like someone repeatedly trying to acquire red or to dump purple. However, with only three rounds (and three turns per round), there is limited time to learn and exploit; many offers will be simple, single-color-for-single-color swaps that lightly favor the proposer while still being acceptable to at least one partner. We forecast a path where players quickly discover mutually beneficial red–purple and blue–red trades, with green used sparingly, and where most offers that are even modestly beneficial to a responder are accepted rather than punished.\n\nIn the forecast below, we treat players as mildly strategic yet boundedly rational: they reason in unit or small-bundle terms, avoid obviously value-destroying trades for themselves, and are willing to accept trades that give them clear positive value differences, even if they may not be globally optimal. We also assume they roughly prefer keeping some diversification across colors rather than fully specializing, especially in a short game.",
